Things to do in Sheffield

Sheffield is a city and metropolitan borough of South Yorkshire, England. Its name derives from the River Sheaf, which runs through the city. Historically part of the West Riding of Yorkshire, the city has grown from its largely industrial roots to encompass a wider economic base.

During the 1740's, a form of the steel making process was discovered that allowed the manufacture of higher quality steel than had previously been possible. This, plus the innovation of the Sheffield Plate, spurred Sheffield's growth as an industrial town. Sadly, the growing population led to the construction of back to back dwellings that, along with the severe pollution from the factories, led to Sheffield being described as the "ugliest town in the old world."

Increased competition in the 1980's saw the closure of many of Sheffield's steel mills. The building of the Meadowhall shopping centre turned out to be a mixed blessing. Though it created a lot of new jobs, it rapidly speeded up the decline of the city centre. Thankfully there were are a number of regeneration schemes to boost the area. These included the building of the Sheffield Arena, Don Valley Stadium and the Ponds Forge complex.

Sheffield has a major sporting heritage, with Sheffield Wednesday and Sheffield United both playing in the Football League. Sheffield Wednesday play at Hillsborough, whilst Sheffield United play at Bramhall Lane. There is also an Ice Hockey team known as the Sheffield Steelers, as well as a rugby league team called the Sheffield Eagles.
